WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:08.792
♪

00:08.792 --> 00:10.750
JOHN: Kick some ass at ballet,
sweetheart.

00:10.750 --> 00:13.667
SAMANTHA: Everyone’s anorexic,
no one has an ass to kick.

00:13.667 --> 00:15.458
What’s the matter?
You wanted to be the swan,

00:15.458 --> 00:16.917
and they made you the lake?

00:16.917 --> 00:18.250
SAMANTHA: I hate ballet.

00:18.250 --> 00:20.125
Mom did what she always does,

00:20.125 --> 00:21.917
signed me up
and then told me I had to go

00:21.917 --> 00:23.417
because she already
signed me up.

00:23.417 --> 00:26.333
JOHN: Mom-Mom does that to me
with karaoke.

00:26.333 --> 00:27.667
SAMANTHA: See you later.

00:27.667 --> 00:29.917
JOHN: Hey!

00:29.917 --> 00:31.333
You want to play hooky?

00:31.333 --> 00:34.917
♪

00:34.917 --> 00:36.291
TROY: Attaboy, John.

00:36.291 --> 00:37.917
Now back to combination one.

00:37.917 --> 00:40.083
Whoo, 70 years young, y’all!

00:40.083 --> 00:43.500
SAMANTHA: Yeah, Pop-Pop! Whoo!

00:43.500 --> 00:46.041
JASMINE: I hope I look like that
when I’m your age.

00:46.041 --> 00:47.417
JOHN: Hey, look at that,

00:47.417 --> 00:50.166
even with a Victoria’s Secret
model around,

00:50.166 --> 00:52.500
everybody’s checking me out,
huh?

00:52.500 --> 00:53.875
SAMANTHA: It looks so fun!

00:53.875 --> 00:55.667
JOHN: Yeah, you want to try it?

00:55.667 --> 00:57.000
SAMANTHA: I don’t think
I should.

00:57.000 --> 00:58.458
Mom doesn’t like violence.

00:58.458 --> 01:00.208
She wouldn’t even
let me do tai chi.

01:00.208 --> 01:03.125
JOHN: Ugh, those people give
the slowest high-fives.

01:03.125 --> 01:06.291
(Jasmine grunting)

01:06.291 --> 01:08.583
JOHN: If Jasmine can do it,
so can you.

01:08.583 --> 01:09.834
Girl power.

01:09.834 --> 01:11.375
Or whatever you girls say

01:11.375 --> 01:14.208
before you talk behind
each other’s backs.

01:14.208 --> 01:16.500
Troy, show her some moves.

01:18.458 --> 01:19.792
TROY: One, two.

01:19.792 --> 01:21.917
One, two.

01:21.917 --> 01:24.750
-Straight.
JOHN: Attagirl, Sam!

01:24.750 --> 01:27.083
(grunting)

01:27.083 --> 01:28.291
TROY: Your girl’s killing it,
man.

01:28.291 --> 01:30.625
JOHN: I know,
looks like me in a wig.

01:30.625 --> 01:32.542
♪

01:32.542 --> 01:33.500
HEATHER: Dad,
I want to thank you

01:33.500 --> 01:34.792
for taking Sam to ballet.

01:34.792 --> 01:36.250
You know, I think
it’s really helping her

01:36.250 --> 01:37.333
with her anger issues.

01:37.333 --> 01:38.792
JOHN: Oh, it’s my pleasure.

01:38.792 --> 01:41.291
You got enough on your plate
with working

01:41.291 --> 01:42.667
and taking care of the kids.

01:42.667 --> 01:45.250
Gosh, you’re practically
a Superman-Woman.

01:45.250 --> 01:47.250
HEATHER: Oh, well, thanks, Dad.

01:47.250 --> 01:50.041
JOHN: Yeah, I’ll drive the kids
to all their activities.

01:50.041 --> 01:51.125
HEATHER: You--you mean that?

01:51.125 --> 01:53.250
Really, I mean you’ll drive
my kids everywhere?

01:53.250 --> 01:54.709
JOHN: Well, yeah.

01:54.709 --> 01:56.959
I mean just Sam,
just to ballet,

01:56.959 --> 02:00.041
and you can give me
gas money later.

02:00.041 --> 02:01.083
HEATHER: That’s fair.

02:01.083 --> 02:05.000
♪

02:05.000 --> 02:07.083
TROY: There we go, stay low.

02:07.083 --> 02:08.709
That’s perfect.

02:08.709 --> 02:09.959
Thirteen years old, y’all!

02:09.959 --> 02:11.875
(cheering)

02:13.583 --> 02:14.834
JASMINE: Damn, she’s tough.

02:14.834 --> 02:17.458
I’m not getting
in the ring with her.

02:17.458 --> 02:18.583
TROY: I thought you were
something special,

02:18.583 --> 02:20.250
but she’s a beast.

02:20.250 --> 02:21.458
JOHN: Yeah, I guess,

02:21.458 --> 02:24.542
if you’re impressed
with someone who can’t drive.

02:25.834 --> 02:27.542
♪

02:27.542 --> 02:29.417
HEATHER: Really? Boxing?
JOHN: Mm-hm.

02:29.417 --> 02:31.458
HEATHER: She knows
that I don’t like violence.

02:31.458 --> 02:33.125
Oh, I am gonna kill her.

02:33.125 --> 02:35.208
I’m as shocked as you are.

02:35.208 --> 02:36.583
I dropped her off at ballet,

02:36.583 --> 02:39.250
and she must have hiked
the six miles to the gym.

02:39.250 --> 02:42.250
HEATHER: Dad, I keep trying
to encourage her to do things

02:42.250 --> 02:43.583
that will suit her,

02:43.583 --> 02:45.333
and she’s just
really resisting me.

02:45.333 --> 02:46.834
I’m at a loss with her, Dad.

02:46.834 --> 02:49.166
Mm-hm. Mm-hm.

02:49.166 --> 02:51.208
So that’s it with boxing?

02:51.208 --> 02:52.500
TROY: One, two.

02:52.500 --> 02:54.166
-One, two.
-This feels good.

02:54.166 --> 02:55.583
It’s all about me again.

02:55.583 --> 02:56.834
TROY: One, two.

02:56.834 --> 02:59.125
All right, let’s wrap it up.

02:59.125 --> 03:01.250
Where’s your granddaughter,
by the way?

03:01.250 --> 03:02.291
Huge potential, that one.

03:02.291 --> 03:05.125
JOHN: Well, turns out it’s all
because of the steroids.

03:05.125 --> 03:06.208
TROY: It’s too bad.

03:06.208 --> 03:07.542
She was the one person
I didn’t have to pretend

03:07.542 --> 03:09.625
to be impressed by.

03:09.625 --> 03:11.333
Great job today, by the way.

03:11.333 --> 03:13.166
SAMANTHA: Pop-Pop!

03:15.166 --> 03:17.291
JOHN: Oh! Hey, Sam, honey.

03:17.291 --> 03:19.333
Yeah, your mom told me you
weren’t going to fight anymore.

03:19.333 --> 03:22.458
I was just telling Troy
how disappointed I was.

03:22.458 --> 03:24.500
You’re not the only one
disappointed.

03:24.500 --> 03:26.333
You betrayed me.

03:26.333 --> 03:27.625
Troy?

03:27.625 --> 03:29.000
He’ll be back in a second.

03:29.000 --> 03:30.750
Boxing was your idea.

03:30.750 --> 03:32.250
You got me hooked,

03:32.250 --> 03:35.000
and now you’re taking it
away from me?

03:35.000 --> 03:37.625
I don’t think so.

03:37.625 --> 03:39.333
Troy?

03:39.333 --> 03:40.834
There’s no one here,

03:40.834 --> 03:44.333
but you, me,
and my two friends...

03:44.333 --> 03:46.125
♪

03:46.125 --> 03:47.333
JOHN: Yeah.

03:47.333 --> 03:49.333
I think you should
let her do it after all.

03:49.333 --> 03:51.333
HEATHER: Okay, you ratted
her out yesterday.

03:51.333 --> 03:53.750
What changed your mind?

03:53.750 --> 03:55.667
I’m jealous, okay?

03:55.667 --> 03:57.917
Of your 13-year-old
granddaughter?

03:57.917 --> 04:00.917
Before she showed up at the gym,
I was the hero there.

04:00.917 --> 04:03.542
Now usually at my age
that means keeping a pigeon

04:03.542 --> 04:05.250
from stealing your sandwich.

04:05.250 --> 04:08.500
Sam comes in,
she stole my sandwich.

04:08.500 --> 04:09.875
She’s really that good?

04:09.875 --> 04:12.291
Oh, she’s a natural.

04:12.291 --> 04:15.375
Like Robert Redford
in that baseball movie.

04:15.375 --> 04:17.417
What’s that called again?

04:17.417 --> 04:18.709
<i>The Natural.</i>

04:18.709 --> 04:21.417
No. Uh-uh, that’s not it.

04:21.417 --> 04:23.458
♪

04:23.458 --> 04:25.291
Oh, do you know what
this place reminds me of?

04:25.291 --> 04:26.333
It reminds me of a place

04:26.333 --> 04:27.792
where I would never
take a child.

04:27.792 --> 04:29.417
What is that smell?

04:29.417 --> 04:32.667
It’s passion
and determination.

04:32.667 --> 04:36.000
Oh, and a possum died
in the locker room.

04:36.000 --> 04:38.291
Okay, let’s just
get her and go.

04:38.291 --> 04:40.709
I mean, hopefully this is
just some weird fascination

04:40.709 --> 04:42.333
that she’ll be over

04:42.333 --> 04:44.083
once she realizes
it’s not forbidden.

04:44.083 --> 04:46.083
Are you sure you want her
to get over it?

04:46.083 --> 04:48.250
(grunting)

04:48.250 --> 04:50.625
Is that Sam?

04:50.625 --> 04:52.333
(grunting)

04:52.333 --> 04:55.375
Oh, my God,
look how strong she is!

04:56.500 --> 04:59.250
See? She’s amazing.

04:59.250 --> 05:00.625
I know this is
not your thing,

05:00.625 --> 05:02.667
but I think Sam
may have found her thing.

05:02.667 --> 05:04.834
Now this was my thing first,

05:04.834 --> 05:08.458
but I’m working
through that now.

05:08.458 --> 05:09.875
♪

05:09.875 --> 05:11.875
I guess she’s at that age,
you know, where I just--

05:11.875 --> 05:16.542
I have to get out of the way
and just let her do her thing.

05:16.542 --> 05:18.583
♪

05:18.583 --> 05:20.375
That’s my girl!

05:20.375 --> 05:22.750
♪

05:22.750 --> 05:24.208
Yeah!

05:24.208 --> 05:25.667
(grunting, thudding)

05:25.667 --> 05:27.750
Oh, oh, honey!

05:27.750 --> 05:29.750
♪

05:29.750 --> 05:31.500
Happens.

05:31.500 --> 05:32.750
♪

05:32.750 --> 05:35.166
JEN: Ah...

05:35.166 --> 05:38.291
TIM: Oh, you been feeling
sad lately, Jen?

05:38.291 --> 05:39.750
JEN: Huh, no, why?

05:39.750 --> 05:41.083
TIM: ’Cause your tongue’s
depressed.

05:41.083 --> 05:42.583
(laughs)

05:42.583 --> 05:44.625
Oh, okay, yeah,
that one was good.

05:44.625 --> 05:45.583
TIM: Actually, it looks
like you have

05:45.583 --> 05:46.875
acute infectious
pharyngitis.

05:46.875 --> 05:49.250
So it means those tonsils
are going to go bye-bye.

05:49.250 --> 05:50.917
What, you have to take
my tonsils out?

05:50.917 --> 05:52.375
Well, just to dinner,
maybe a movie.

05:52.375 --> 05:54.583
I’ll have them home by 10:00.

05:54.583 --> 05:56.291
-Another one...
TIM: Yeah.

05:56.291 --> 05:57.208
Actually,
when you think about it,

05:57.208 --> 05:58.834
you’ve been on antibiotics
six times

05:58.834 --> 05:59.750
in the last two years,

05:59.750 --> 06:01.625
so surgery’s
the best option.

06:01.625 --> 06:04.125
No, no. No,
I don’t have time for surgery.

06:04.125 --> 06:05.542
TIM: Oh, surgery’s fast.

06:05.542 --> 06:08.542
And I won’t see you naked,
if that’s on your mind.

06:08.542 --> 06:09.834
It is now.

06:09.834 --> 06:11.417
TIM: Anyway,
Heather will schedule

06:11.417 --> 06:12.375
something for you this week

06:12.375 --> 06:14.875
and we’ll castrate
those throat testicles.

06:14.875 --> 06:17.458
(door opens)

06:17.458 --> 06:20.709
I mean, he called my tonsils
"throat testicles."

06:20.709 --> 06:23.000
Maybe that’s
the medical term for them.

06:23.000 --> 06:25.250
I feel like I should
get a second opinion.

06:25.250 --> 06:27.000
All right, then get
a second opinion.

06:27.000 --> 06:28.250
Yeah, but he’s family.

06:28.250 --> 06:30.125
I mean, if he found out
I got a second opinion,

06:30.125 --> 06:32.500
do you know the drama-rama
that’s going to ensue?

06:32.500 --> 06:35.083
You know how awkward
a dinner table’s gonna be?

06:35.083 --> 06:37.250
Okay, so then get the surgery.

06:37.250 --> 06:39.000
I mean, he’s a good doctor.

06:39.000 --> 06:41.375
And if not,
you’re a good lawyer.

06:41.375 --> 06:43.166
Come on, this is serious.

06:43.166 --> 06:44.750
You’re right, it is.

06:44.750 --> 06:46.208
It’s a conundrum.

06:48.333 --> 06:50.250
Greg, the answer
is not in your beard.

06:50.250 --> 06:51.166
Hmm?

06:51.166 --> 06:52.500
JEN: Ah...

06:52.500 --> 06:54.667
Yeah, yeah,
they’re certainly infected,

06:54.667 --> 06:57.834
but I think a tonsillectomy
is a bit of overkill.

06:57.834 --> 06:58.750
You do?

06:58.750 --> 06:59.709
Oh, that’s such a relief.

06:59.709 --> 07:01.500
Because my other doctor said
I needed to have them removed.

07:01.500 --> 07:03.458
But he also called them
"throat testicles,"

07:03.458 --> 07:06.291
which was a medical term
I was unaware of.

07:06.291 --> 07:07.959
You know, there are
some similarities.

07:07.959 --> 07:10.250
Yeah, they’re both round,
and they’re both glands,

07:10.250 --> 07:13.208
and you can have them removed
and still be a man.

07:13.208 --> 07:16.375
Right, well,
that felt oddly personal.

07:16.375 --> 07:17.500
Well, the antibiotics

07:17.500 --> 07:19.041
are gonna take care
of that infection,

07:19.041 --> 07:21.125
but we’re going to give you
a throat culture just in case.

07:21.125 --> 07:22.542
And I’m going
to send your file

07:22.542 --> 07:25.667
with my recommendations
back over to Dr. Hughes.

07:25.667 --> 07:26.917
JEN: What?

07:26.917 --> 07:28.000
No, no, no!

07:28.000 --> 07:29.625
No, no, no! No!

07:29.625 --> 07:31.083
Oh!

07:31.083 --> 07:32.417
Ah...

07:32.417 --> 07:34.208
Can you please not stand
this close to me?

07:34.208 --> 07:36.291
Because you’re
incredibly sick.

07:36.291 --> 07:38.333
Right, right, right.

07:38.333 --> 07:39.875
♪

07:39.875 --> 07:41.500
I mean, Tim probably gets
hundreds of e-mails

07:41.500 --> 07:42.583
from doctors every day.

07:42.583 --> 07:44.000
Plus his Joke-A-Day e-mails?

07:44.000 --> 07:45.375
I mean, he can’t read them all.

07:45.375 --> 07:46.583
Well, I hope you’re right.

07:46.583 --> 07:48.458
Otherwise, I don’t know
how I’m going to face him.

07:48.458 --> 07:50.875
Although, it would
probably be less painful

07:50.875 --> 07:52.667
than one of the bad jokes
he’s going to tell.

07:52.667 --> 07:54.166
Mm...

07:54.166 --> 07:57.500
TIM: You guys hear
about the corduroy pillow?

07:57.500 --> 07:59.959
It’s making headlines.

07:59.959 --> 08:01.333
HEATHER: Oh!

08:01.333 --> 08:03.250
Okay, I didn’t get that
at first,

08:03.250 --> 08:05.917
but then when it hits you,
it hits you hard.

08:05.917 --> 08:08.291
-I think we’re okay.
-Yeah, no, they don’t know.

08:08.291 --> 08:09.667
WAITRESS:
Everything tasting okay?

08:09.667 --> 08:11.834
Any coffee or tea?

08:11.834 --> 08:13.917
JEN: Um, I would love,
like, an herbal tea.

08:13.917 --> 08:15.834
WAITRESS: We have a delicious
honey vanilla chamomile tea.

08:15.834 --> 08:17.166
JEN: Yeah, that sounds good.

08:17.166 --> 08:18.166
HEATHER: Whoa, whoa, whoa, no.

08:18.166 --> 08:20.250
Oh, Jen, you don’t want
to just take her word for it.

08:20.250 --> 08:21.458
No, oh, come on.

08:21.458 --> 08:23.208
Why don’t you ask this guy?

08:23.208 --> 08:25.083
Right here, you know,
get the opinion of someone

08:25.083 --> 08:27.417
that you’ve never even met.

08:27.417 --> 08:28.709
Here we go.

08:28.709 --> 08:30.291
HEATHER:
Sir, my sister-in-law here

08:30.291 --> 08:32.542
just got a very solid
recommendation

08:32.542 --> 08:33.959
for the chamomile tea,

08:33.959 --> 08:35.875
but she’d like to know
your thoughts.

08:35.875 --> 08:37.792
WAITER: I’m more of
a eucalyptus passion fruit guy.

08:37.792 --> 08:39.375
TIM: Well, there you go, Jen!

08:39.375 --> 08:41.500
I’m sure the opinions
of this random waiter

08:41.500 --> 08:42.750
that you have
no connection with

08:42.750 --> 08:44.166
must mean a whole lot
more to you

08:44.166 --> 08:48.083
than your first waitress,
who’s practically family.

08:48.083 --> 08:49.083
JEN: You know what? No.

08:49.083 --> 08:52.583
I’m actually glad I got
the other waiter’s opinion

08:52.583 --> 08:54.542
because eucalyptus
passion fruit dude

08:54.542 --> 08:58.500
saved me
from unnecessary surgery.

08:58.500 --> 08:59.667
WAITRESS:
I’ll just bring both teas.

08:59.667 --> 09:00.834
HEATHER: No, no, no, no, no,

09:00.834 --> 09:03.208
because you cannot have it
both ways, Jen.

09:03.208 --> 09:07.417
You see, because when
you seek out that second tea,

09:07.417 --> 09:10.417
the first tea cries
in front of a patient.

09:10.417 --> 09:12.250
TIM: You know what,
I can’t eat this.

09:12.250 --> 09:13.834
Just bring me a cinnamon roll.

09:13.834 --> 09:14.750
HEATHER: It’s okay.

09:14.750 --> 09:16.458
♪

09:16.458 --> 09:18.875
(phone beeps)

09:18.875 --> 09:20.500
It’s a voicemail
from Dr. Antro.

09:20.500 --> 09:21.417
DR. ANTRO:<i> Hi, Jen.</i>

09:21.417 --> 09:22.542
(coughs)

09:22.542 --> 09:25.000
<i>This is Dr. Antro calling.</i>

09:25.000 --> 09:28.083
<i>Not because you got me sick,</i>
<i>which you did,</i>

09:28.083 --> 09:30.208
<i>but because after looking</i>
<i>at your test results,</i>

09:30.208 --> 09:33.291
<i>I actually would</i>
<i>recommend surgery.</i>

09:33.291 --> 09:35.083
Oh, no.

09:35.083 --> 09:36.917
Surgery?

09:36.917 --> 09:40.375
The good news is we do have
a doctor in the family.

09:40.375 --> 09:42.583
Oh, no, no, no,
no, no, no.

09:42.583 --> 09:43.834
♪

09:43.834 --> 09:46.041
Look, I’m sorry
that I didn’t trust you.

09:46.041 --> 09:47.500
TIM: It’s okay, it’s okay.

09:47.500 --> 09:48.792
Let me see what we got.

09:48.792 --> 09:50.083
Next week, no.

09:50.083 --> 09:51.625
Next year, no.

09:51.625 --> 09:53.875
I could do one tonsil
in December.

09:53.875 --> 09:55.875
HEATHER: Oh, no, wait,
here’s one, honey, right there,

09:55.875 --> 09:57.083
right in the year of the rat!

09:57.083 --> 09:58.083
JEN: Okay, all right.

09:58.083 --> 10:00.500
I can see that there’s still
a lot of anger here.

10:00.500 --> 10:01.667
TIM: You’re a lot of anger!

10:01.667 --> 10:03.041
Wow.

10:03.041 --> 10:05.458
Don’t know why
I ever doubted you.

10:05.458 --> 10:08.208
TIM: It’s all I needed to hear.

10:08.208 --> 10:10.333
Bring it in. Come on.

10:10.333 --> 10:12.375
-Give me a hug.
-Oh, oh, okay.

10:12.375 --> 10:14.458
TIM: Come on, there you go.
-Thanks.

10:14.458 --> 10:15.917
TIM: Actually,
I shouldn’t be touching you,

10:15.917 --> 10:17.250
you are very sick.

10:17.250 --> 10:19.875
♪

10:19.875 --> 10:21.750
MATT: Would you stop trying
to please my mother?

10:21.750 --> 10:23.083
She already kisses you
on the lips.

10:23.083 --> 10:24.458
That’s as far
as you want it to go.

10:24.458 --> 10:26.458
That’s as far
as you want it to go.

10:28.917 --> 10:32.291
♪

10:32.291 --> 10:33.625
JOAN: Here, dear,
here’s something

10:33.625 --> 10:35.333
to nibble on until we order.

10:35.333 --> 10:36.291
MATT: Aw, actually,

10:36.291 --> 10:38.417
Colleen doesn’t really like
garlic bread.

10:38.417 --> 10:39.875
COLLEEN: No, but this is
a garlic knot,

10:39.875 --> 10:42.083
which is totally different
and yummy.

10:42.083 --> 10:43.625
And there’s probably
not enough garlic on it

10:43.625 --> 10:45.667
to trigger my allergy.

10:45.667 --> 10:48.875
Thank you. Thank you so much.

10:48.875 --> 10:50.792
Would you stop trying
to please my mother?

10:50.792 --> 10:52.083
She already kisses you
on the lips.

10:52.083 --> 10:53.500
That’s as far
as you want it to go.

10:53.500 --> 10:55.583
That’s as far
as you want it to go.

10:55.583 --> 10:58.750
JOAN: And don’t think I forgot
about you, sweetheart.

10:58.750 --> 11:00.291
MATT: Thanks, Mom.

11:00.291 --> 11:02.625
Oh, no, no, no, no!

11:02.625 --> 11:03.542
COLLEEN: What happened?
MATT: Get it, Sam!

11:03.542 --> 11:05.750
(commotion)

11:05.750 --> 11:07.291
HEATHER: What? What?
What happened?

11:07.291 --> 11:10.166
JOAN: Oh! I put a spider
in his...

11:10.166 --> 11:11.625
JOHN: In his knots!

11:11.625 --> 11:14.166
She got him right in the knots.

11:15.583 --> 11:16.959
JOAN: That is the best one yet.

11:16.959 --> 11:18.500
I think he tooted.

11:18.500 --> 11:19.834
COLLEEN: Funny stuff.

11:19.834 --> 11:21.125
Is this a thing you all do?

11:21.125 --> 11:22.583
How did I not know
this was a thing?

11:22.583 --> 11:24.500
MATT: Because every time
she does it, I keep on hoping

11:24.500 --> 11:28.166
that she will remember that
she is a therapist and stop it.

11:28.166 --> 11:32.333
JOAN: I will stop
when it stops being funny.

11:32.333 --> 11:35.709
Besides, you won’t overcome
your arachnophobia

11:35.709 --> 11:38.208
unless you expose yourself
to spiders.

11:38.208 --> 11:40.375
MATT: I was never scared
of spiders as a kid

11:40.375 --> 11:42.583
until you started sticking them
in my lunchbox.

11:42.583 --> 11:44.208
Colin McGrath used to get
sweet little notes

11:44.208 --> 11:46.000
from his mom telling him
how special he was.

11:46.000 --> 11:47.375
JOAN: What’s funny about that?

11:47.375 --> 11:49.500
HEATHER: Oh, Mom, come on,
you have to stop scaring us.

11:49.500 --> 11:50.667
It’s not cool.

11:50.667 --> 11:52.250
GREG: She used to hide
in the basement

11:52.250 --> 11:53.417
and then jump out and scare me

11:53.417 --> 11:55.166
when I would go down there
to play bumper pool.

11:55.166 --> 11:56.917
I had to quit playing.
Could’ve gone pro.

11:56.917 --> 11:59.375
-He was good.
JOAN: It’s a tradition.

11:59.375 --> 12:03.000
My mom did it to me,
and I do it to you all.

12:03.000 --> 12:05.458
And, someday, you get
to do it to your kids.

12:05.458 --> 12:06.667
MATT: Okay, have your laughs.

12:06.667 --> 12:08.542
But if you think
I’m throwing in any cash

12:08.542 --> 12:10.333
at the end of this dinner,
you’re wrong.

12:10.333 --> 12:12.125
JOHN: And there goes
the excuse of the week.

12:12.125 --> 12:13.542
JOAN: John, stop.

12:13.542 --> 12:14.750
♪

12:14.750 --> 12:17.166
COLLEEN: There’s something
I want to show you.

12:17.166 --> 12:19.458
MATT: There’s something
I want to show you, too.

12:19.458 --> 12:20.917
(gasps)

12:20.917 --> 12:22.625
COLLEEN: It’s fake! It’s fake.

12:22.625 --> 12:24.208
Your mom wanted me
to put it on your chest

12:24.208 --> 12:26.208
while you were sleeping.

12:26.208 --> 12:27.750
She’s sick! She’s a sicko!

12:27.750 --> 12:29.750
Now she’s trying
to turn you against me, too?

12:29.750 --> 12:30.834
-Mmm.
-I know, it’s like

12:30.834 --> 12:32.417
she’s sweet her whole life

12:32.417 --> 12:34.667
so her personality
can have a cheat day.

12:34.667 --> 12:37.250
And there’s nothing I can do
about it, she won’t stop.

12:37.250 --> 12:39.000
What if you made her?

12:39.000 --> 12:41.875
What if you exposed her
to one of her fears?

12:41.875 --> 12:44.125
What’s she afraid of?

12:44.125 --> 12:46.542
She’s afraid that the bagger
at the grocery store

12:46.542 --> 12:47.500
is going to give her a hug?

12:47.500 --> 12:48.458
MATT: No, dude, that’s you.

12:48.458 --> 12:49.792
She’s afraid of being
wrongfully imprisoned.

12:49.792 --> 12:52.333
I mean, that’s why she had
to stop watching<i> 48 Hours.</i>

12:52.333 --> 12:54.291
Oh, wearing tennis shoes
on the escalator

12:54.291 --> 12:55.917
and her laces get caught.

12:55.917 --> 12:59.750
GREG: No, I don’t think
we’ve got it yet.

12:59.750 --> 13:01.667
What about perch,
the fish?

13:01.667 --> 13:04.291
I’m afraid of them because one
once bit me in a lake.

13:04.291 --> 13:06.375
-Huh.
COLLEEN: Mm-hm, yeah.

13:06.375 --> 13:08.917
HEATHER: Ooh, I got it.
MATT: What, what, what?

13:08.917 --> 13:13.250
HEATHER: She is deathly afraid
of Dad’s new robot vacuum.

13:13.250 --> 13:14.667
GREG: Yes.
-Boom.

13:14.667 --> 13:16.041
GREG: Yeah, she’s afraid
it’s going to come to life

13:16.041 --> 13:17.250
and watch her in the shower.

13:17.250 --> 13:18.834
MATT: And we can make it
come to life.

13:18.834 --> 13:21.291
Uh, does Sophia have any
remote-controlled cars?

13:21.291 --> 13:24.000
I don’t know,
do perch have teeth?

13:24.000 --> 13:26.208
Nasty little suckers.

13:26.208 --> 13:33.125
♪

13:37.000 --> 13:39.750
Okay, come on, come on.
Let’s go, we have to hurry.

13:39.750 --> 13:42.333
We only have 15 minutes
until Dad’s back from boxing.

13:42.333 --> 13:43.959
No, Mom comes down
for a bowl of ice cream

13:43.959 --> 13:45.750
between 9:00 and 9:06 p.m.

13:48.000 --> 13:49.959
It was really healthy for me
to move out of the garage.

13:49.959 --> 13:51.000
HEATHER: Oh, dude.

13:51.000 --> 13:53.417
(vacuum beeping)

13:59.166 --> 14:00.709
COLLEEN: Okay, go, go, go!

14:00.709 --> 14:01.542
MATT: Here we go.

14:08.542 --> 14:10.417
-Oh, no.
COLLEEN: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

14:12.500 --> 14:14.625
JOAN: Oh, no! No, no!

14:14.625 --> 14:16.458
No! No!

14:16.458 --> 14:18.041
No!

14:18.041 --> 14:19.875
I told John this was
going to happen.

14:19.875 --> 14:21.250
No, no, no!

14:21.250 --> 14:22.959
(Joan screams)

14:22.959 --> 14:24.000
This is so good.

14:24.000 --> 14:25.625
JOAN: No, no, no!

14:25.625 --> 14:26.917
Down!

14:26.917 --> 14:28.375
Down, robot!

14:28.375 --> 14:30.417
(laughing)

14:30.417 --> 14:31.792
Okay, good.

14:31.792 --> 14:33.041
No!

14:33.041 --> 14:34.625
Ah! John!

14:34.625 --> 14:35.834
Oh, we got a runner.

14:35.834 --> 14:38.125
(excited overlapping chatter)

14:38.125 --> 14:39.041
(loud thud)

14:39.041 --> 14:40.542
GREG: Oh, no!

14:40.542 --> 14:41.583
COLLEEN: That’s not good.

14:41.583 --> 14:43.333
GREG: Mommy!

14:43.333 --> 14:45.625
COLLEEN: Oh, no.

14:45.625 --> 14:48.000
GREG: Are you okay?
JOAN: I think so.

14:48.000 --> 14:49.250
GREG: Oh, you’re bleeding.

14:49.250 --> 14:51.208
Quick, get the first aid kit
under the sink.

14:51.208 --> 14:52.667
HEATHER: Go, go, go!
Come on, go!

14:52.667 --> 14:54.834
I got this, I’m a doctor’s
office receptionist.

14:58.875 --> 15:00.917
MATT: Oh, my God, oh, my God!

15:00.917 --> 15:02.834
No! No!

15:02.834 --> 15:05.667
Bug spray, bug spray,
bug spray...

15:05.667 --> 15:07.667
♪

15:07.667 --> 15:10.166
(screams)

15:10.166 --> 15:13.959
♪

15:13.959 --> 15:15.333
Are you kidding me?

15:15.333 --> 15:16.583
JOAN: We got him!

15:16.583 --> 15:17.917
You were in on this?

15:17.917 --> 15:19.291
COLLEEN: I’m sorry.

15:19.291 --> 15:21.166
I just really want
your mom to like me.

15:21.166 --> 15:23.625
(laughing)

15:28.083 --> 15:29.166
MATT: Hope you guys
are real happy together.

15:29.166 --> 15:30.709
-Aww!
-Come on!

15:30.709 --> 15:33.417
There’s still
a tarantula in there!

15:33.417 --> 15:34.542
COLLEEN: I love you!

15:34.542 --> 15:35.834
♪

15:35.834 --> 15:39.291
GREG: My beard is just
vacuuming up that wax.

15:39.291 --> 15:40.875
It was so dry.

15:40.875 --> 15:42.250
A storm must be coming.

15:44.333 --> 15:47.417
♪

15:47.417 --> 15:50.458
Oh, God, honey,
when are you going to shave?

15:50.458 --> 15:52.250
I thought you’d be done
with that thing by now.

15:52.250 --> 15:54.542
Nope, no,
I’m just getting started.

15:54.542 --> 15:56.250
-What?
-Well, yeah, I figured

15:56.250 --> 15:57.417
now that I’m home every day,

15:57.417 --> 15:59.041
I’ve really got
to look the part.

15:59.041 --> 16:01.166
Of what? An Amish farmer?

16:01.166 --> 16:03.208
Come on, give it a stroke.

16:03.208 --> 16:07.125
I really--I miss kissing
my smooth-faced husband.

16:07.125 --> 16:09.000
I mean, we could get it on
without kissing,

16:09.000 --> 16:11.250
it’s just I know how much
that upsets you.

16:11.250 --> 16:13.166
You’ll come around,
you will.

16:13.166 --> 16:15.208
Just wait until
it softens up a little bit.

16:15.208 --> 16:17.208
In fact, I just got
this new shampoo for beards.

16:17.208 --> 16:19.166
It’s going to help.
It’s called Beard-Poo.

16:19.166 --> 16:20.709
♪

16:20.709 --> 16:22.375
HEATHER: Ugh, yeah,
I feel your pain.

16:22.375 --> 16:25.250
Tim went through a beard phase
and I hated it.

16:25.250 --> 16:26.542
You know,
I think he was just happy

16:26.542 --> 16:28.291
that he could
grow hair somewhere.

16:28.291 --> 16:31.208
Well, Greg thinks it makes him
less likely to get mugged.

16:31.208 --> 16:33.041
HEATHER: Yeah, Tim grew his

16:33.041 --> 16:35.333
so that we could play student
and professor.

16:35.333 --> 16:37.125
I still always end up
playing the professor.

16:37.125 --> 16:39.750
But I did come up
with the perfect plan

16:39.750 --> 16:41.542
to get him to shave it.

16:41.542 --> 16:43.333
♪

16:43.333 --> 16:44.917
GREG:<i> Man,</i>

16:44.917 --> 16:48.417
my beard is just vacuuming up
that wax.

16:48.417 --> 16:49.959
It was so dry.

16:49.959 --> 16:51.333
A storm must be coming.

16:51.333 --> 16:55.000
Well, whatever you’re doing
is working.

16:55.000 --> 16:58.041
It’s natural and rugged
and makes me feel

16:58.041 --> 17:01.125
like you could
build us a deck.

17:01.125 --> 17:03.625
-Really?
-Yeah.

17:03.625 --> 17:05.291
So you’re on board
with the beard, huh?

17:05.291 --> 17:08.917
Totally. In fact,
I’ve decided to join you.

17:08.917 --> 17:11.333
Yeah. I stopped shaving, too.

17:11.333 --> 17:12.542
What do you mean?
Like your legs?

17:12.542 --> 17:14.792
Like my everything.

17:14.792 --> 17:18.250
Whole kit and caboodle.

17:18.250 --> 17:20.166
But when--when we’re sleeping

17:20.166 --> 17:21.834
and our legs
accidentally touch,

17:21.834 --> 17:23.291
they will have
stubble on them?

17:23.291 --> 17:24.500
Well, at first.

17:24.500 --> 17:26.166
But don’t worry
because in time,

17:26.166 --> 17:29.250
it’ll all just be long
and curly, like your face.

17:29.250 --> 17:30.917
Yeah, okay,
I see what you’re doing.

17:30.917 --> 17:32.000
-Ha.
-This is the trick

17:32.000 --> 17:34.083
that Heather pulled
to make Tim shave his beard.

17:34.083 --> 17:35.166
Yeah, that’s not going to work.

17:35.166 --> 17:36.875
What? You knew about that?

17:36.875 --> 17:38.792
Yeah.

17:38.792 --> 17:40.834
Tim is not a beard guy.

17:40.834 --> 17:43.875
It looked like his head
was on upside-down.

17:43.875 --> 17:45.583
Good night.

17:45.583 --> 17:47.208
♪

17:47.208 --> 17:48.291
Here you go.

17:48.291 --> 17:50.125
The breakfast of champions.

17:50.125 --> 17:52.041
JEN: Oh, babe...

17:52.041 --> 17:54.667
Can you please
just shave the beard?

17:54.667 --> 17:55.750
For me?

17:55.750 --> 17:57.542
Don’t you see?

17:57.542 --> 18:01.333
All along, I thought
I was grooming the beard.

18:01.333 --> 18:03.458
But it turns out
the beard was grooming me.

18:03.458 --> 18:04.583
Oh.

18:04.583 --> 18:06.166
And, besides, Lark likes it.

18:06.166 --> 18:07.583
Don’t you?

18:07.583 --> 18:08.709
Don’t you?

18:08.709 --> 18:11.083
You like the beard, don’t you?

18:11.083 --> 18:12.208
Don’t fear the beard.

18:12.208 --> 18:14.125
(gasps)

18:15.875 --> 18:17.208
Wow.

18:17.208 --> 18:19.709
She took the vomit
right out of my mouth.

18:19.709 --> 18:20.750
I’m going to go clean up.

18:20.750 --> 18:23.041
(crying)

18:23.041 --> 18:24.041
♪

18:27.000 --> 18:28.208
♪

18:28.208 --> 18:30.625
WAITRESS: It’s been really great
serving you guys.

18:30.625 --> 18:32.583
I hope to see you again soon.

18:35.959 --> 18:37.458
MATT: What is that smell?

18:37.458 --> 18:38.792
GREG: It’s my beard.

18:38.792 --> 18:40.291
Lark puked in it.

18:40.291 --> 18:41.417
Can you smell it?

18:41.417 --> 18:42.709
TIM: Not that you deserve
my advice,

18:42.709 --> 18:44.625
but any time I want to cover up
an unwanted smell

18:44.625 --> 18:48.500
coming from my body,
I go to one place: Benihana.

18:48.500 --> 18:50.667
You don’t stop smelling,
but you smell like shrimp.

18:52.625 --> 18:55.125
You know what,
I can’t finish this.

18:55.125 --> 18:56.917
Bring me a cinnamon roll.

18:56.917 --> 18:58.458
Cinnamon roll!

18:58.458 --> 19:01.166
♪

19:01.166 --> 19:02.291
GREG: Hey.

19:02.291 --> 19:03.375
JEN: Oh, my God!

19:03.375 --> 19:04.834
Oh, no, no, it’s worse!

19:04.834 --> 19:06.166
Oh, no, how can it be worse?

19:06.166 --> 19:09.959
Now it smells like vomit
on a hibachi.

19:09.959 --> 19:11.333
GREG: But in a good way?

19:11.333 --> 19:12.709
JEN: I’m so sorry, honey.

19:12.709 --> 19:14.208
I love you, I do,

19:14.208 --> 19:17.542
but you, like, legit
repulse me right now.

19:17.542 --> 19:20.542
But in, like, a good way, right?

19:20.542 --> 19:22.500
Okay, fine,
I will shave my beard.

19:22.500 --> 19:24.667
-You will?
-Yes.

19:24.667 --> 19:25.834
Yes!

19:25.834 --> 19:27.917
GREG: There are plenty of ways
for me to be a modern man.

19:27.917 --> 19:29.125
Yeah.

19:29.125 --> 19:30.417
What do you think of those disks

19:30.417 --> 19:32.917
that people put in their ears?

19:32.917 --> 19:34.834
("Goodbye Stranger"
by Supertramp plays)

19:34.834 --> 19:38.917
MALE SINGER:<i> ♪ And I really</i>
<i>have enjoyed my stay ♪</i>

19:38.917 --> 19:41.125
<i>♪ But I must be moving on ♪</i>

19:41.125 --> 19:44.041
(whirring)

19:44.041 --> 19:46.041
<i>♪ Like a king</i>
<i>without a castle ♪</i>

19:46.041 --> 19:48.125
<i>♪ Like a queen</i>
<i>without a throne ♪</i>

19:48.125 --> 19:52.667
<i>♪ I’m an early-morning lover</i>
<i>and I must be moving on ♪</i>

19:52.667 --> 19:54.583
<i>♪ Good-bye, stranger ♪</i>

19:54.583 --> 19:56.500
<i>♪ It’s been nice ♪</i>

19:56.500 --> 19:58.625
<i>♪ Hope you find your paradise ♪</i>

19:58.625 --> 20:00.208
Ow, ow!

20:00.208 --> 20:03.375
(crying)

20:03.375 --> 20:04.500
No, I...

20:04.500 --> 20:05.834
You can do this!

20:05.834 --> 20:07.250
MALE SINGER:<i> ♪ All come true ♪</i>

20:07.250 --> 20:09.000
<i>-♪ Good-bye, Mary ♪</i>
<i>-♪ Good-bye, Mary ♪</i>

20:09.000 --> 20:10.917
<i>-♪ Good-bye, Jane ♪</i>
<i>-♪ Good-bye, Jane ♪</i>

20:10.917 --> 20:12.834
<i>♪ Will we ever ♪</i>

20:12.834 --> 20:14.458
<i>♪ Meet again? ♪</i>

20:14.458 --> 20:16.291
GREG: Hey.

20:16.291 --> 20:18.458
Guess who doesn’t smell
like puke anymore.

20:18.458 --> 20:22.375
Oh, there’s the man I married.

20:22.375 --> 20:24.208
(groans)

20:24.208 --> 20:26.917
Sorta.

20:26.917 --> 20:27.875
’Sup?

20:27.875 --> 20:30.417
Um, you look...

20:30.417 --> 20:34.375
super sexy.

20:34.375 --> 20:37.875
But I’m just--I’m a little bit
worried about my throat.

20:37.875 --> 20:38.792
(coughs)

20:38.792 --> 20:42.125
Okay, just this once
we’ll do it without kissing.

20:42.125 --> 20:43.333
All right.

20:43.333 --> 20:50.250
♪
